List of results so far:
- `φ ^ (n + 2) - φ ^ (n + 1) = φ ^ n`
- `2 > φ`
- `fib (n + 1) - φ * fib n = ψ ^ n`
- `fib n + φ * fib (n + 1) = φ ^ n`

Already in mathlib as a special case of `Nat.fib_dvd` (note that `fib 5 = 5`).
```lean
example (n : ℕ) : 5 ∣ fib (5 * n) := by
  nth_rw 1 [show 5 = fib 5 by rfl]
  exact fib_dvd _ _ (Nat.dvd_mul_right _ _)
```
Oh! Yeah, you are right. I wanted to prove the more general result from https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence#Primes_and_divisibility.
Since the most general result (`Nat.fib_gcd`) is already there you should remove your changes to `Data.Nat.Fib.Basic` entirely.
Done
If you are adding new theorems you shouldn't add the `align` line (don't worry about it if you don't know what it does, it is related to an old version of Lean).

```suggestion
theorem two_gt_gold : φ < 2 := by
```
I am surprised the linter didn't catch this!

This should probably be called something like `gold_pow_sub_gold_pow` or `gold_pow_recurrence` (the former is more in line with Mathlib naming conventions). But `exp` references things like [Complex.exp](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/Complex/Exponential.html#Complex.exp), or [Real.exp](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/Complex/Exponential.html#Real.exp) or [NormedSpace.exp](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Analysis/NormedSpace/Exponential.html#NormedSpace.exp).

You can refer to the [naming conventions](https://leanprover-community.github.io/contribute/naming.html) for more details.

Note, we use `ring` when the tactic closes the goal. `ring` and `ring_nf` don't do *quite* the same thing.
```suggestion
  rw [goldenRatio]; ring_nf; norm_num; ring
```

1. we would call this `gold_lt_two` because of the direction of the inequality.
2. If you haven't learned about the `gcongr` tactic yet, let this be your introduction. It's very handy, and the `sqrt_lt'` allows us to get rid of the resulting `sqrt` lying around.
```suggestion
theorem gold_lt_two : φ < 2 := by calc
    (1 + sqrt 5) / 2 < (1 + 3) / 2 := by gcongr; rw [sqrt_lt'] <;> norm_num
    _ = 2 := by norm_num
```
We have a relationship between these quantities just above in `Real.coe_fib_eq`. Is there a reason you prefer to have this relationship explicitly?

It formalises the relation given by The Art of Computer Programming: Volume 1: Fundamental Algorithms, 1.2.8. The other result also comes from Knuth but is given by David Wells Curious and Interesting Numbers, also George Bergman Number System with an Irrational Base.
Same question here, although this one doesn't involve `goldenConj`, so that's a reason to include it separately.

```suggestion
theorem fib_golden_exp' (n : ℕ) : φ * Nat.fib (n + 1) + Nat.fib n = φ ^ (n + 1) := by
  induction n with
  | zero => norm_num
  | succ n ih =>
    calc
      _ = φ * (Nat.fib n) + φ ^ 2 * (Nat.fib (n + 1)) :=
        by simp only [Nat.fib_add_one (Nat.succ_ne_zero n), Nat.succ_sub_succ_eq_sub, tsub_zero,
          Nat.cast_add, gold_sq]; ring
      _ = φ * ((Nat.fib n) + φ * (Nat.fib (n + 1))) := by ring
      _ = φ ^ (n + 2) := by rw [add_comm, ih]; ring
```
It's probably possible to gold it even more, but who cares.
